Ken Elkins


Staff Writer





In This Article






Springs Global




Crandall Close Bowles






 


 















 Enlarge





                Crandall Bowles            






The big headline for Crandall Close Bowles in 2007 centers on what she isn't doing anymore.
Bowles and the Close family cashed out most of its equity in Springs Global this year as the company went public in a $300 million Brazilian stock offering. The family kept only 5% of the textile giant that was founded in 1887 in Fort Mill by Bowles' great-great grandfather, Samuel Elliott White, and great grandfather, Leroy Springs.











 Enlarge





                Crandall Bowles            






 


Bowles resigned from her position as co-chief executive at Springs Global, handing power to her Brazilian partner, Josue Christiano Gomes da Silva.
"In the current stock offering, my family will sell a significant portion of our Springs Global holdings. I will continue to serve on the board of Springs Global," Bowles said in July. "I will leave knowing that our company has survived radical change and emerged with solid market value. I have great confidence in my co-CEO and successor, Josue Gomes, and the rest of the management team."
The process that led to Bowles departure started in January 2006 when Springs Industries Inc. merged with Brazilian textile giant Coteminas, forming Springs Global.
The merger combined Springs' sheet and towel operations with Coteminas' fabric production, making the consolidated company the world's largest home-furnishings manufacturer.
In the end, the merger that formed Springs Global US put the company in a position to survive the dramatic decline of the U.S. textile industry, industry analysts say.
What did Springs get out of the deal? The low-cost production capabilities of its Brazilian partner, Coteminas.
Bowles had become the fifth generation of the Springs family to run the company in 1998. She served 10 years as chief executive of an independent Springs Industries. At the time of her appointment, industry watchers speculated that she was brought in to make the tough decisions: cutting jobs and closing plants as the nation in 1995 saw an end to the international textile quota system, which had limited imports from low-wage countries.

When the nation's borders were thrown open to inexpensive home-textile imports, Springs, Pillowtex Corp., J.P. Stevens and other U.S. textile companies couldn't compete.
In the first of Bowles's strategies to stay afloat in a sea of inexpensive home-fashion textile imports, the family formed a partnership with an investment fund to take the company private.




 


Springs formed its first alliance with Coteminas in 2001.
As more production moved off shore, Springs Global began rapidly shuttering U.S. plants starting in 2004 with the closing of the Lyman plant in Lyman, S.C., and the Wamsutta plant in Anderson, S.C., eliminating 540 jobs. It concluded with the end of all manufacturing in its home state in 2007 as production was halted at the Grace plant in Lancaster and the Close plant in Fort Lawn.
"The closing of these plants reflects the global nature of the textile industry, which has made U.S. textile manufacturing uncompetitive," Bowles said in a prepared statement at the time the final closings were announced. "Though inevitable for the company, this move is a sad and difficult one for my family and the people and communities involved. We would like to express our deepest appreciation to all the associates for their years of commitment and productive efforts for this company."
In between was the loss of 1,460 jobs at the Frances and Elliott plants in Fort Lawn and the Katherine plant in Chester. In 1992, Springs employed 14,000 in South Carolina.
Now, 700 Springs Global workers remain in South Carolina, mostly at distribution centers in Fort Lawn and Lancaster and at the former Springs Industries headquarters in Fort Mill.
Although she remains on the Springs Global board, Bowles has started a part-time post as a senior advisor to the N.C. Department of Commerce. Her job is to monitor N.C. businesses' competitiveness in various industry sectors.
Bowles's husband, former Charlotte investment banker Erskine Bowles, is the president of the 16-campus UNC System.
Despite Bowles' and the Close family's virtual departure from Springs Global, both will be forever linked to the Fort Mill area, where family land holdings count in the thousands of acres.
On 1,000-plus acres between Interstate 77 and the Catawba River, the family built a successful neotraditional neighborhood called the Village of Baxter. It was one a series of villages planned for family land in the area.







 





 















































 

























































