Bizspace Spotlight
        





 Sponsor Listing 



                    Property Spotlight: WestChase III                




See All Bizspace Properties



 







 



Crandall Close Bowles is the latest in a family of leaders at the helm of Springs Global US Inc., the 120-year-old textile giant formerly known Springs Industries Inc., based in Fort Mill, S.C., until its merger this year with Brazil's Coteminas.
Bowles' grandfather, Col. Elliott White Springs, helped launch the company. Her father, H.W. "Bill" Close, expanded the corporation and took it public. In 2001, Bowles returned it to private ownership.




 


Leadership is never far from her, even at home. Her husband, Erskine Bowles, is president of the University of North Carolina System, a two-time U.S. Senate candidate and former chief of staff in the administration of President Bill Clinton.
Crandall Bowles joined Springs Industries as an executive vice president in 1992, held several assignments and was appointed president and chief operating officer in 1997. She became chairman and chief executive in 1998.
She recently discussed the challenges of leadership as part of the Leaders In Action speakers' series at Queens University of Charlotte's McColl Graduate School of Business. Edited excerpts of an interview afterward follow:





What kinds of leaders were your father and grandfather?
Most leaders end up being strong one way or another. Both started working in the plants. My grandfather, being the founder, knew everything about the business. He was very visionary in where he saw the company going. He also had a group of men who he relied on.
My father had an expanded group of people he worked with and was more relationship-oriented. He was a better delegator. I would say he understood where the company was going and had the opportunity to expand.
In the 1960s, he took the company public. He also had the courage to bring in the first outsider, Peter Scotese, to serve as president. He brought the company more into the modern corporate world.
I once read that your first job was at the Peach Stand (a market and restaurant in Fort Mill). Did you learn anything there about working with people that serves you today?
I made 50 cents an hour. I certainly learned the discipline of knowing to be on time. It's more about dealing with different people than anything else. It's part of a process that teaches you that the customer is always right.





 


How do you describe your leadership style?
My leadership style has evolved. It's collaborative. I came into the textile business later in my career. There were people who knew more about the business and I rely more on their experience and judgment.
I bring a logic and a willingness to challenge preconceived notions and the way things "have always been done." I've had to lead through tremendous change in the industry. (At Queens) I talked about leading a company through a transition that had a lot of difficult or negative connotations for the people that are working in this area.
Do you feel there are unique leadership skills that are required in the textile industry? Have the skills you use changed as the industry has changed?
You have to be willing to change. You get kind of dragged along, and you can't be in denial. You have to be willing to see that things have to change and can't operate in the same way.
Your husband is a prominent leader as well. Do you ever discuss leadership strategies at home?
Not really. He has a different approach and one that's objective. We talk about being on different boards. He's got a lot of leadership opportunities and is following two very strong leaders (as UNC System president), Dick Spangler and Bill Friday.








 






