U.S.
| AFTER THE ELECTION: THE PLAYERS -- Man in the News 
A Southern Point Man: Erskine Boyce Bowles

By TODD S. PURDUMNOV. 9, 1996



Continue reading the main story
Share This Page

Continue reading the main story









When President Clinton summoned his Vice President, his chief of staff and his chief of staff-to-be to join him on a small platform in the East Room of the White House today, he gestured to the gold carpet behind him and said, ''No particular order.''Erskine B. Bowles, the reedy, owlish North Carolina businessman whom Mr. Clinton has pressed into service to lead the White House into a second term, moved instinctively to the background. That is the spot Mr. Bowles grew used to as a deputy chief of staff for 15 months until he left last December to return to the private sector.''We're two Southern guys,'' Mr. Bowles said in an interview last spring, summing up his bond with his boss. ''I didn't want anything. I didn't talk to reporters. I came from a world where your relationship with your clients was confidential and he was my only client. I think he felt comfortable that I could listen.''Now he will be front and center in one of the most visible, high-pressure jobs in the country. Mr. Bowles, a multimillionaire investment banker and 1992 fund-raiser who went on to become head of the Small Business Administration and then the President's golfing partner, time manager and trusted friend, will not only have to listen but also to talk. And he will have dozens of demanding constituents, from senators to Cabinet secretaries to anchormen.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Yet if most of those who saw the East Room ceremony on television today were hearing Mr. Bowles's voice for the first time, few who know him seem to think he will have much trouble adjusting to the task. Continue reading the main story







Advertisement

Continue reading the main story





''A grand slam,'' said Commerce Secretary Mickey Kantor, who once upon a time in 1992 aspired to the job himself. ''He is tremendously loyal, but it's a loyalty that promotes candor and straight talk. At the same time, he's very graceful and gracious, which can't be overestimated when you're in a caldron like the White House.''Mr. Clinton himself said he turned to Mr. Bowles, whom he has described as his best friend in the White House, because he wanted ''someone of stature, intellect, dedication, drive, and the capacity to do this virtually impossible job.''Mr. Clinton's first chief of staff was his childhood friend, Thomas F. McLarty 3d, who was widely regarded as nice but ineffectual, and the President eased him out in the summer of 1994 in favor of Leon E. Panetta, a former Congressman from California. Mr. Panetta brought new discipline to the staff, but wanted to return to California to contemplate a run for governor.Mr. Bowles, 51, is a far closer, locker-room pal, one Mr. Clinton has relied on for delicate tasks, from telling Dick Morris that he had to resign as the Clinton campaign's political strategist after reports in August that he had a relationship with a prostitute, to overseeing the President's preparation for campaign debates this fall.He has long been the President's first choice to succeed Mr. Panetta, but he had to be persuaded, having just last January started a merchant banking concern that specializes in buying mid-sized companies on behalf of investors. Mr. Bowles agreed to rejoin the Administration in a phone conversation Thursday night.In a brief interview, Mr. Bowles said today that his partners had agreed to buy him out. He said he had told Mr. Clinton that he ''wanted to have some input'' in choosing his own team, in part because he wants people to compensate for his own inexperience in dealing with Congress. Other White House aides said that was a polite way of saying that Mr. Panetta's two deputies, Harold M. Ickes and Evelyn Lieberman, would almost certainly not stay on.As co-deputy chief of staff with Mr. Bowles under Mr. Panetta, Mr. Ickes served as political strategist and ambassador to Democratic constituency groups, while Mr. Bowles oversaw internal administration and the President's time. The two made a good team but have little in common.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Mr. Bowles is no stranger to politics. He comes from a prominent North Carolina family and his late father, Hargrove Bowles was the Democratic candidate for governor of North Carolina in 1972. His wife, Crandall Close Bowles, is the sister of Elliot S. Close, who lost his challenge to Senator Strom Thurmond of South Carolina this week.
Newsletter Sign Up
Continue reading the main story

  


