The Closes are descendants of the family that founded Springs Industries, the South Carolina textile giant that makes Springmaid and Wamsutta sheets, and Mrs. Bowles is the company's executive vice president and head of its bath division and a candidate for the top job one day. Company records show that she is a millionaire many times over. She was a Wellesley College classmate of Hillary Rodham Clinton's.Mr. Bowles, who graduated from the University of North Carolina and holds an M.B.A. from Columbia University, met Crandall Close when they worked at Morgan Stanley & Company in New York in the early 1970's. He left in 1975 to found Bowles, Hollowell, Conner & Company, a regional investment bank in Charlotte, where Mr. Bowles made another, smaller fortune of his own.At the ceremony today, Mr. Bowles warmly thanked his family for their support as ''we together have reached this enormous decision for me to once again return to Washington and leave my family behind in North Carolina.'' In a sign of the separations to come, neither his wife nor any of their three college-age children could be there; all were grounded by bad weather and unable to fly to Washington.Mr. Bowles had not known Mr. Clinton before the 1992 campaign, when he helped raised about $1.5 million for Mr. Clinton's campaign. But they formed a strong bond over Mr. Bowles's son Sam, who suffers from diabetes. In a car one day after a campaign event, Mr. Bowles, then the president of the national Juvenile Diabetes Foundation, complained about President George Bush's ban on fetal tissue research, which could hold hope for a cure.Mr. Clinton paid little overt attention at the time, Mr. Bowles recalled last spring, but in a speech a short while later, told the story of Sam Bowles, promised to end the ban if elected, then did so and sent Sam the pen he used to sign the order.Named by Mr. Clinton to head the Small Business Administration, Mr. Bowles streamlined loan applications and other programs and received high marks for managing the agency. He came to the White House in 1994, bonding further with the President as he helped Mr. Panetta control access to the Oval Office and carve out more free time for the President to think, write and plan.Mr. Bowles has a reputation as a polite perfectionist who is quick with praise, but also demanding. He used to advise anyone who showed up for an 8 A.M. meeting at 8:05 that they need not bother.''I think he's more interested in people respecting him than in liking him,'' said one senior White House aide who both likes and respects him, ''and the way he deals with people is very up-front.''

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

PROFILEErskine Boyce BowlesBorn: Aug. 8, 1945, Greensboro, N.C.Hometown: Charlotte, N.C.Education: Virginia Episcopal School; University of North Carolina; Columbia University Graduate School of Business.Career Highlights: Founder of Carousel Capital, an investment banking firm in Charlotte, January 1996; White House deputy chief of staff, 1994-95; Administrator, United States Small Business Administration, 1993-94; chairman, Bowles Hollowell Conner & Company, an investment banking firm he founded in 1975 in Charlotte; Morgan Stanley & Company in New York; president, Juvenile Diabetes Foundation.Family: Married to Crandall Close; two sons and a daughter.Hobbies: Running. Continue reading the main story






